1. What is a POJO Class?

POJO stands for Plain Old Java Object.

A POJO class contains only data members, constructors,
getter/setter methods and business methods.

It does not contain the main() method.

Example:

Person.java

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Entity Class

An Entity class stores only data.

Example

Person

Data Members

• id
• name
• address
• phoneNumber

---------------------------------------------------------

3. Executor Class

The Executor class contains the main() method.

It is responsible for creating objects and executing the
program.

Example

Executor.java

---------------------------------------------------------

4. Why Separate POJO and Executor Class?

• Better code organization
• Easy maintenance
• Reusability
• Follows Object-Oriented Programming principles

---------------------------------------------------------

5. Instance Variable

Variables declared inside a class but outside methods.

Example

private int id;
public String name;

These variables belong to the object.

---------------------------------------------------------

6. Local Variable

Variables declared inside a method.

Example

public void display(){

    int x = 10;

}

Local variables exist only inside that method.

---------------------------------------------------------

7. Reference Variable

A reference variable stores the address of an object.

Example

Person p = new Person();

Person -> Class Name

p -> Reference Variable

new -> Memory Allocation Operator

Person() -> Constructor

---------------------------------------------------------

8. Object Creation

Syntax

ClassName objectName = new ClassName();

Example

Person p = new Person();

